  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Helps detect and prevent money laundering\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. Title III of the USA PATRIOT Act\n- Expanded anti-money laundering requirements\n- Enhanced reporting and compliance regulations\n- Increased international cooperation in combating money laundering\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing money laundering laws\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\nAt the state level, many states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\nThese statutes generally define money laundering as the process of making illegally obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex transactions or legitimate businesses. Penalties can include significant fines and imprisonment.\n\nFederal agencies like the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) and the Department of Justice are primarily responsible for investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses.",
